{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_kendall_ver01/data/sn82014085/00393346826/1945092101/0247.xml":{"full_text":"Anticipate Rise In\nLiving Prices In *46\nElliott S. Boordmon of Boston Addresses\nAccountants on Future Business Outlook\nr\nk>. Dvni uuittii, manager oi\nth* Statistical Division of the Fed\neral Reserve Bank of Boston,\nspeaking at the opening meeting of\nthe Hartford Chapter of the Na\ntional Association of Cost Account\n\u2022nts at the Farmington Country\nclub, Tuesday evening, predicted a\nmixed outlook for 1646. He expects\nthe coming year will have a con\ntinued rise In prices as was wit\nnessed after the first world war\nwhen prices rose more In the one\nand a half years between Nov. 11,\n1618, and 1830, than during the\ntwo full years.\nMr. Boardman described the ac\ntivities of the Federal Reserve\nBanks of Boston and Its efforts\nthrough research to aid business,\nchart economic trends and manu\nfacturing activities as well as the\nusual banking functions. He paid\ntribute to Ralph Flanders, president\nof the bank, for his leadership and\nactivities as an Industrialist, In\nvestor and effort In the Com\nmittee of Economic development.\nMr. Boardman displayed to the ac\ncountants a series of charts pre\npared by the bank's research de\npartment, showing the trends of\nIndustrial production, durable goods\nand non-durable goods and min\nerals, wholesale prices, factory em\nployment and* payrolls. National\nIncome In relation to national debt\nwas discussed In detail by Mr.\nBoardman. Our national Income in\n1820 was 80 billion dollars and\nISO billion dollars In 1644 and to\nmeet our federal spending expect\nancy (20 to 30 billion), a national\nIncome of 140 billion will be need\ned. Our national debt was 50 million\nIn 1630 as agalnts 283 billion today.\nThe next decade, continued Mr.\nBoardman, will probably witness the\ngreatest federal spending In the his\ntory of this country barring the\nwar years\nIf the unemployment benefits are\nAccountants\nPlan Dinner\n\u25a0Oov. Raymond E. Baldwin will be\nthe guest speaker at the Sept. 25\ndinner meeting of the New Haven\nchapter, National Association of\nCost Accountants.\nArthur Stinson, program director\narranged this event as a Joint meet\ning with the New Haven area mem\nbers of the Manufacturers Associ\nation of Conn. The New Haven\nLawn club has been secured to ac\ncommodate the large attendance ex\npected for the governor's talk.\nOov. Baldwin plans an Important\nmessage regarding the rehabilita\ntion of business and Industry, the\nsubject of his discussion at the re\ncent conference of New England\ngovernors.\nRestoration Fund\nGiven $80,000 Gift\nAn unsolicited gilt of 180,000 to\nthe Restoration Fund, Presbyterian\nchurch, U. S. A., was announced\nyesterday by Frank M. Totton, Na\ntional Chairman of the Laymen's\nCommittee.\nMr. Totton said the gift was from\nan anonymous donor who specified\nthe sum was to be used for re\nbuilding Presbyterian schools and\nchurches in the Philippines and\nChina that were destroyed in the\nwar.\nThis is the first subscription to\nthe Presbyterian 137,000,000 Cam\npaign, which is aimed at the res\ntoration of the religious agencies in\nthe war-devastated countries.\nPROGRAM FOR MOURNERS\nRockingham, N. C. (UP)\u2014Henry\nC. Ellerbe of Wolf Pitt township\n(Richmond county) was a highly\nrespected NegTO citizen when he\ndied at the age of 89, recently. His\nkin took five days to prepare for\nhis burial. A printed program was\ndistributed to the mourners cover\ning the ceremonies.\nraised by law to the requested $25\nper week the recipient will b able\nto purchase less than the former\n$20 benefit due to the Increased\ncost. Continued deficit spending Is\na certain contribution to Inflation.\nThe speaker believes we do not want\na stable society which would leave\nno latitude or profit for honest\neffort. Though New England has\nfewer war monuments of factories\nsuitable olny for war production\nthan many other sections of the\ncountry, Industrial cities In New\nEngland do face and will continue\nto face the problem of the North\nern New Englander who has spent\nwar years In this area and de\nveloped mechanical knowledge and\ntraining. This knowledge and high\nearnlngB will keep him in the Indus\ntrial area with a natural reluctance\nto return to the lower comparative\nearnings of his former occupation.\nFour Killed\nIn Bus Crash\nAlbany, N. Y., Sept. 21\u2014(UP)\u2014\nState police and bus company offi\ncials sought today to Identify the\nbodies of one man and three women\nkilled in a bus accident west of New\nLebanon Center, Columbia county.\nTwenty-three othws were injured,\ntwo 'critically.\nThe Interstate bus, traveling from\nAlbany to Pittsfield, Mass., left the\nhighway last night, crashed Into a\npole and burst Into flames, It was\nreported. State police said at least\nfour bodies could be seen in the\ncharred wreckage.\nThe Injured were taken to hos\npitals in Troy and Pittsfield.\nNames of four of the Injured have\nbeen withheld pending notification 1\nof their families, and an unidenti\nfied sailor was reporetd treated and.\nreleased at one of the Pittsfield hos\npitals.\nThe Identified Injured were listed\nPvt.Raymond Bronson, Bridge\nport, Conn.\nPrank Stlrrot, Pittsfield,\nSumner Knight, Beckett, Mass.\nRaymond Verina, Dover, N. H.\nRaymond Picard, Tyngsboro,\nMass.\nArland Lamb, Pittsfield, Mass.\nRalph Volk, Pittsfield, Mass.\nMrs, Veronica Vezina, Dover, N.\nH.\nMrs. Thomas Purey, Pittsfield.\nRobert Willie, North Adams.\nPrank Del Rossi, Gardner, Mass.\nPrank P. Isbttello, Lawrence,\nMass.\nMrs. Gloria Del Rossi, Gardner,\nMass.\nTwo New Firms\nRecord Papers\nJoseph M. Cassln, Marie W. Cas\nein, both of this city, and John H.\nCa&sldy, Watertown, are lnoorp\norators of the Cassln Realty Co.,\nwhich hu been formed with an au\nthorized capital of $76,000, accord\ning: to a certificate of Incorporation\nfiled with the Secretary of State at\nHartford.\nThe Community Market, Inc.,\nNaugatuck, Is also being incorpor\nated with paid In property of $6,000.\nStocks consist of 140 shares of $50\nTWO YEARS TO PAY\nNow you can buy an oil burner\nfor your furnace and bays com\nplete automatic heating. No more\ncoal and aahee to handle. Guar\nanteed uniformity of temperature\nand save money at the same time.\nYes, our oil burner in yeur fur\nnace will cost you lesa to operate\nthan coal.\nWe Do Furnace Cleaning and\nRepairing\nTHE WATERBURY\nHEATING CO.\n34-36 SPRING ST. 4-647$\nESTABLISHED IMS\nYou may possibly think Rogers*\nPoet suits and topcoats at $55\nto $95 expensive clothing for\nmen. It isn't\u2014wisely thrifty\nbankers who know the value of a\ndollar, who throw away no dollars\nand who are very keen on making\nsure they get their dollars' worth\nfor dollars expended wear Rogers\nPeet good clothes for two reasons\n\u2014They cost less by the year than\nany other clothes they've ever\nworn, because they wear more\nyears and they look better right\ndown to the last thread while giv\ning this wonderfbl service.\nThousands of other men wear\nRogers-Peet clothes for the same\nreasons and thus the growing\nnumber of Rogers-Peet enthusi\nasts keeps growing by leaps and\nbounds as the news gets around.\n\nmmmm\nCrew Of Record Breaking B-29\n(INP Sound Photo)\nTired, but happy, the crew of the B-*9 commanded by Lt.-Gen. Barney Glleo, have their picture taken\nbefore their plane after flying non-itop from Japan to Chicago. (Left to right) (Front row) Lt. S. K.\nMartin, Lt. Harold Nfrhood, Lt. Milton S. Berman, Lt. Burnell Cilery. (Back Row) Capt. W. G. Howes;\nLt. Robert E. Bates, Lt. Glenn E. Whatley and Lt. William Dolan, Jr.\npur vaiue. umcers are: president,\nJames P. Sullivan; vice-president,\nEvelyn Clrello; secretary, Elizabeth\nSullivan, and treasurer, Martin\nOlrello, all of Waterbury.\nWaterbury Burns Club\nPlans to Be Discussed\nThe Waterbury Burns Club will\nhold a meeting tomorrow night at\n8:30 to make plans for their fall and\nwinter program. William Sherrif,\nvice-president will preside at the\nmeeting and all members are asked\nto attend.\nBoard Hears\nComplaints\nOf Drivers\nUnion Discrimina\ntion Charged;\nSecond Hearing\nOrdered\nEdward P. Grady, owner of the\nYellow Cab Co., la expected to\ntestify before the State Labor Re\nlations Board Oct. 2 when a hear\ning is resumed on an American Fed\neration of Labor charge that he dis\nmissed four taxi drivers because of\nunion activities. The first session\nwas held yesterday afternoon at the\ncounty courthouse building on Ken\ndrick avenue.\nThe workers claim they were dis\ncharged last month because they\nJoined the union. The quartet, com\nposed of Peter Poley, Rocco Copo\nbianco, Henry Shaker and William\nRoblnofsky, testified yesterday. Four\nother drivers who appeared before\nthe board Included: John Diorlo,\nWilliam Goggins, Joseph Howell\nand Michael Manglacottl.\nAttorney Maurice Wrenn and\nTimothy Collins of the Truck Driv\ners Local 677 appeared for the dis\ncharged men, While Attorneys\nMichael V. Blansfield and Michael\nCiano represented the Cab Com\npany.\nGrady through his counsel claim\nWOUN\n{HINT\n(OUAH.\nHtVI HIE d]\nWONDER WEAVER!\ned that Shaker wee find after It\nwaa discovered he sold liquor from\na cab. Detective Joseph McCarthy\nwas called as a witness for Grady\nand testified that Shaker admitted\nto him that he had sold liquor once.\nOne of the men was fired for\nstealing gasoline, another for being\nlate to work, and another for taking\na day off from work, according to\nstatements made In behalf of\nGrady.\nThe four men claimed that Grady\nasked them If they had joined a\nunion, and they were discharged\nsoon after they admitted they had.\nThe board which Is handling the\ncase was set up by the Governor to\ndeal with unfair labor practice cases.\nPresent for the session yesterday\nwere: Ashbel G. Gulliver, chairman,\nState Senator Vincent Kleman, and\nPeter A. McManus. John A. Gasplc,\nInvestigating agent for the board,\nwas among those who testified.\nGraduate Nurses\nMay Take Courses\nA two-credit, fifteen weeks course,\n\"Current Trends In Nursing\u201d will be\noffered at St. Mary\u2019s Hospital In\nWaterbury by the University of\nConnecticut School of Nursing. The\nREGENCY\nHOUSE\nTOPCOATS\nv We have a\nj handsome selec\ntion of our fa\nmous Imported\nand English\n{styled topcoats.\nClothier* Tenor* Fernluhero\n*40 '55\n126 BANK ST.\nOSCPH\u2019S\nmd registration nu\nhoepilel at the claa\nSept. 34. Olaaaes wUl\nMonday evening* from\nMies Delia Newton. B.\nW*et Hartford, will\ncourse.\nIt means smart style,\ncarefully selected and\npresented at low prices\nby a courteous staff.\nHATS\n$1.25\n$28.50\nRemember\nthis label...\n_\nWavr&r\nDRESSES\nS598,oU0\u00bb8\n\u2022'Waterbary*.\nr w.iuukM\n\u25a0tun*\n74 SOUTH MAIN ST.\nI\n(MM* ln AUI|\njVou) Only--\nTERMS TO SUIT\u2019.\nJO^CJEDROOM\nYou Got*\nW\u00bb\\\u00bbutBed\nCho\u00bbtofDrft\nC \\r or Vanity\nDre\u00bb\u00bb Spring\nSimmon* CoU 3P\nBetter\u00ae*1 M^e**\n2 Pittovr\u2018\nBoudoir Chair\n2 Boudoir Lamp*\nTTuVtMGSSSE\nYou Get:\nMode*\u201d Sot\n^\"chin\u00ab Loun,.\ncSitfiT-*.\ntVS TriS\n5 Pwute\u2018\n\u2022\u00ae3=-i\nINCLUDE\u00ae!\n\u201cFamous\nWide B*\u00ab\nu\u00abih*\nblnAtnC*'\nctt(tomer\nIT'S EASV\nR1 lPGET-1.\nNo\nblon\u00ab>\nDown\niMm&M\n\u00a3ve.\nPHONE' 0'3\n,vtorM..M\u2018D*4\nMgr\n\u00bbU c**\u20191 JJJ JSS?\ne^itolWe0t\nconvenl*\"0*\nrefui*1\n*rr\u00bbn*\u00ab\nto\nKF^IiE\nYou\nInlaid top\n4 LwtHerott*\nChoir*\n\u201eo pc. Br\u00ab\u00bb\nluncheon 8","height":"28392","width":"20868"}}
